column4: This is for unitless numbers.  It is always formatted as General and cannot be changed

This is used for lengths that measure something on a piece of paper rather than in a physical building, like font sizes, dash lengths in a line pattern definition, and various distances in dimension style properties.  It cannot be changed directly.  Rather, it is determined by the UT_Length settings.  If UT_Length is set to anything imperial, UT_SheetLength uses fractional inches.  If UT_Length is set to anything metric, UT_SheetLength uses millimeters.
Used for property line angles.  It is always formatted as Degrees Minutes Seconds and cannot be changed
These cannot be set directly.  They are determined by whether the corresponding UT_Force, UT_LinearForce, UT_AreaForce or UT_MomentScale is imperial or metric.
Is not used. Seems like redundant

This is similar to UT_SheetLength but much more rarely used.  It uses decimal inches rather than fractional inches.  It is used in places where for whatever reason we prefer decimal inches, for example printer margin settings.

column1: Note on Unit types which fall under all discplines:
The units that fall under all discplines will throw an exception just like we cannot access them in project units setting in UI. These are special cases and they cannot (or no need to) be modified.
